The remaining population, in the lower left of the figure, is characterized by shorter periods and smaller period derivatives. These are so-called “millisecond pulsars” (MSPs), thought to arise from “recycling” of rotation speed due to accretion of matter from a binary companion. MSPs are stellar zombies, brought back from the dead with immense rotational energies imparted by infalling matter (Alpar et al. 1982; Radhakrishnan and Srinivasan 1982). The rotation frequencies achievable through this spin-up are impressive—the fastest known rotator is PSR J1748−2446ad at 716 Hz (Hessels et al. 2006). One progenitor class for MSPs is the set of low mass X-ray binaries (LMXBs) in which the neutron star (∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
