				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r$$\end{document}-modes,” due to fluid motion of neutrons (or protons) in the crust or core of the star. Like jet streams in the Earth’s atmosphere that manifest Rossby waves, these currents are deflected by Coriolis forces, giving rise to spatial oscillations (Andersson 1998; Bildsten 1998; Friedman and Morsink 1998; Owen et al. 1998). These r\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r$$\end{document}-modes can be inherently unstable, arising from azimuthal interior currents that are retrograde in the star’s rotating frame, but which are prograde in an external reference frame. As a result, the quadrupolar gravitational-wave emission due to these currents leads to an increase in the strength of the current. This positive-feedback loop leads to a potential intrinsic (Chandrasekhar–Friedman–Schutz; Chandrasekhar 1970; Friedman and Schutz 1978) instability. The frequency of such emission is expected to be a bit more than approximately 4/3 the rotation frequency (Andersson 1998; Bildsten 1998; Friedman and Morsink 1998; Owen et al. 1998; Kojima 1998; Caride et al. 2019).

