Hough transform methods refer, in practice, to an application of a pattern recognition algorithm first developed for use in the 1960’s by high energy particle physicists (Hough 1959, 1962) to reconstruct a charged particle’s trajectory from discrete positions (“hits”), measured by a tracking detector. The method is best suited to data that is “sparse” and for which a simple transformation from the raw measurements to the signal parameter space can amplify the detection statistic. In the original application to particle tracking, the hits were two-dimensional projections for which looking for straight lines built out of all hit combinations was computationally intensive (especially in the 1960’s!). To represent a straight line, instead of offset and slope, the vector of its minimum distance to the origin, in polar coordinates (r,θ)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(r,\theta )$$\end{document}, is used. A point (x, y) belonging to that line sets the relation r=xcosθ+ysinθ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r=x\cos \theta +y\sin \theta $$\end{document} which is a sinusoidal curve in the θ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\theta $$\end{document}-r plane. Cells in that plane count how many curves pass within their boundaries, and the most occupied cell identifies (r,θ)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(r,\theta )$$\end{document} of the original track.

