The same method was applied to an Einstein@Home search in Advanced LIGO O1 data for three supernova remnants: Cas A, Vela Jr. and G347.3 (Ming et al. 2019). Figure 23 shows the results of the three searches, together with results from the coherent search of a subset of the same data set (Abbott et al. 2019a). The semi-coherent search which exploits the full data set, typically achieves a factor of two improvement in strain sensitivity over the coherent search over a data subset. This search also applied a search optimization method (Ming et al. 2016) to choose coherence times and segmentations for each source, where the optimization attempts to take into account relative probabilities for detection, given available astronomical information. In this instance the segmentations chosen were 12 245-h segments (Cas A), 8 369-h segments (Vela Jr.) and 6 489-h segments (G347.3). As seen in Fig. 23, best upper limits obtained were ∼1×10-25\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
